741. In this line we are in- debted to Nonius for preserving the genuine phrase luci claro, which is generally obliterated in our mss. Comp. Ter. Ad. v 3, 55 cum primo luci, where the Bombinus has primo Iucu, while prima luce is found in recent mss. (see Bentley’s note): Do- natus, whose notes are here interpolated, has however a genuine remark on this pas- sage veteres masculino ,qenere dicebant lucem-Flam. Cist. 11 1, 48 B gives quom primo luci and the mss. of Nonius give the same phrase in a line of Atta 468, 32=Ribb. Com. p. 138. But in Cic. de off. 111 31, 112 all the mss give cum prima luce.— In a fable of Ennius rendered in prose by Gellius 11 29 (Enn. ed. Vahlen p. 160) we have primo luce, which is the reading of the cod. Reg. of Gronovius, recent mss having prima luce.— The phrase Luci claro is quoted from Varro's Synephebus by Nonius 210; see Vnum, Bip. ed. p. 309.-1n general comp. Cha- risius p. 203 ed.
